                  <handDesc>
                     
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Fine and regular.</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black and red (vivid vermillion).</seg>
                        <date>18th cent.</date>
                        <seg type="rubrication">Nomina sacra; names of Kings Yoḥannǝs IV and
                           Bäkaffa; the word salām; several lines or groups of lines on the page
                           opening the commemorative notices for each month; one or two initial
                           lines of each commemorative notice; elements of the punctuation signs
                           (e.g., nine dot asterisks in red and black, separating the commemoration
                           notes and the days); elements of Ethiopian numerals; the name Rufāʾel and
                           its abbreviations in Addition 1.</seg>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <list>
                        <item xml:id="a1">
                           <locus target="#1v">f. 1v</locus>
                           <desc>: Crude unclear note.</desc>
                           <quote xml:lang="gez"/>
                           <quote xml:lang="en"/>
                           <note> Crudely written note, barely legible due to dirt and water stains.
                              With an old way of writing the letter ፙ. </note>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a2">
                           <locus target="#4r">ff. 4r</locus>
                           <desc>-v: Malkǝʾa Rufāʾel "Image of Raphael" (ChRep 199, n</desc>
                           <locus target="#131">131</locus>).<quote xml:lang="gez"/>
                           <quote xml:lang="en"/> Written in a well trained hand, in red and black.
                           The name of the scribe is Tewodosyos (s. <locus target="#4vc">4vc</locus>
                           <note>). </note>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a3">
                           <locus target="#219rb">f. 219rb</locus>
                           <desc>: Donation note.</desc>
                           <quote xml:lang="gez">
                              <locus target="#219rb">219rb</locus>: ዝ፡ ስንክሳር፡ ዘታቦተ፡ አማኑኤል፡ ዘወሀቦ፡
                              ንጉሥነ፡ ዮሐንስ፡ መፍቀሬ፡ እግዚአብህሔር፡ በመዋዕለ፡ መምህራኒነ፡ አቡነ፡ ወልደ፡ ዮሐንስ፡ ወአቡነ፡ ወልደ፡
                              ኢየሱስ፡ በረከቶሙ፡ የሀሉ፡ ም[ስ]ሌነ፡ አሜን። ሰላም፡ ሰላም፡ ለንጉሥነ፡ ዮሐንስ፡ ዘተኃርየ፡ እምከርሥ፨
                              ወሰላም፡ ለእሉ፡ መምርራነ፡...</quote>
                           <quote xml:lang="en"/> Written in a fine, trained hand in red and black
                           ink. Some parts are illegible. Possibly the same hand that wrote the name
                           Yoḥannǝs in the supplication formulas throughout the Ms. The note states
                           that the Ms. was donated by King Yoḥannǝs IV to the church dedicated to
                           ʾAmanuʾel, the abbots of the church are ʾabuna Walda Yoḥannǝs and
                              ʾabuna<note> Walda ʾIyasus. </note>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="e1">- A short ownership note (<locus target="#5r">5r</locus>,
                           upper margin) hints to the former owner, the church Madḫāne ʿĀlam, which
                           is the church at Mäqdäla founded by Tewodros II (r. 1855-68).
 - The
                           name Rufāʾel is written in “negative” writing, in <locus target="#219v">219v</locus>, in “white” (colour of the parchment) writing on black
                           ink background, by leaving blank the space for the letter (s. EAE III,
                           741).
 - Erased notes: <locus target="#1v">1v</locus>, 37rc, 219v,
                           220r, 220v.
 - Minor notes and writing exercises: <locus target="#6r">6r</locus>, 33v, 90r, 163r, 140v, 196r, 202v.
 - Pagination in a
                           recent hand in Arabic and Ethiopic numerals in the upper corner of the
                           Ms.</item>
                     </list>
                  </additions>
